      "solution": "n  = int(input())\nb = bin(n)[2:]\nsize = len(b)\n\nfirst_half = b[:size//2]\nfirst_revs = \"\".join([{'0':'1','1':'0'}[c] for c in first_half])\nfirst_number = first_revs + b[size//2:]\n\nsecond_half = b[size//2 + size%2:]\nsecond_revs = \"\".join([{'0':'1','1':'0'}[c] for c in second_half])\nsecond_number = b[:size//2 + size%2] +  second_revs\n\nprint(int(first_number, 2) * int(second_number, 2))",
      "statement": "Given an integer [[n]], find the product [[m]] of the 2 numbers obtained by inverting the {{first}} then the {{second}} half of the binary representation of [[n]].\n\n<<Example:>>\n[[n]] = 8: the binary representation is 1000. the {{first half inverted}} is : {{01}}<<00>> which is 4, and the {{second half inverted}} is <<10>>{{11}} which is 11. so the output [[m]] is 4*11 = 44.\n\n<<Note:>>\nif the length of the binary representation of [[n]] is odd, <<the middle element does not belong to any of the halves>>.\n<<Example:>>\n[[n]] = 5: the binary representation is 101. the {{first half inverted}} is : {{0}}<<01>> which is 1, and the {{second half inverted}} is <<10>>{{0}} which is 4. so the output [[m]] is 1*4 = 4.",
